Same function as good solution, plus sibling merge helper and version-vector extension notes.

```sql
-- After all five writes, remaining siblings:
SELECT version, items FROM ch6_cart_siblings
WHERE cart_id = 'cart-42' ORDER BY version;
-- v4: ["eggs","milk","ham"]
-- v5: ["milk","flour","eggs","bacon"]

CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION ch6_merge_carts(p_cart_id TEXT, p_merged JSONB)
RETURNS INT LANGUAGE plpgsql AS $$
DECLARE v_max INT; v_new INT;
BEGIN
  SELECT MAX(version) INTO v_max FROM ch6_cart_siblings WHERE cart_id = p_cart_id;
  DELETE FROM ch6_cart_siblings WHERE cart_id = p_cart_id;
  v_new := v_max + 1;
  INSERT INTO ch6_cart_siblings VALUES (p_cart_id, v_new, p_merged);
  RETURN v_new;
END;
$$;
```

Use a set-union CRDT with tombstones for production merge — not plain `DISTINCT` union (cart item deletion bug). For this exercise, manual merge of the two sibling arrays documents the need for CRDT.

Multi-replica extension: replace `INT version` with `JSONB version_vector` e.g. `{"r1":3,"r2":2}` — each replica increments its own counter; concurrent if neither vector dominates component-wise. "The collection of version numbers from all the replicas is called a version vector."

Read path:
```sql
SELECT jsonb_agg(items) FROM ch6_cart_siblings WHERE cart_id = $1;
```
returns all siblings for client-side merge.

Write without base_version: treat as concurrent with everything — "it will not overwrite anything—it will just be returned as one of the values on subsequent reads."

Operational: monitor sibling count per key; sustained growth signals unresolved conflicts. Riak flags siblings in API responses the same way.

Comment: Amazon DynamoDB revision-based conditional writes are the managed version of "include version from prior read"; this table simulates Riak's sibling behavior in SQL.
